.SH NAME
SVGPatternElement.width \- SVGPatternElement: width property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]width\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]SVGPatternElement\f[R] interface describes the width of the
pattern as an \f[CR]SVGAnimatedLength\f[R].
It reflects the computed value of the \f[CR]width\f[R] attribute on the
\f[CR]<pattern>\f[R] element.
.PP
The attribute value can be a \f[CR]<length>\f[R],
\f[CR]<percentage>\f[R], or \f[CR]<number>\f[R].
The numeric value of the \f[CR]SVGAnimatedLength.baseVal\f[R] represents
the width of the pattern in the user coordinate system.
.SH VALUE
An \f[CR]SVGAnimatedLength\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLE
Given the following SVG:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]svg\f[R] viewBox=\(dq0 0 200 200\(dq xmlns=\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/2000/svg\(dq>
  <\f[B]defs\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- First pattern \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]pattern\f[R]
      id=\(dqpattern1\(dq
      x=\(dq50\(dq
      height=\(dq20\(dq
      width=\(dq20\(dq
      patternUnits=\(dquserSpaceOnUse\(dq>
      <\f[B]circle\f[R] cx=\(dq10\(dq cy=\(dq10\(dq r=\(dq10\(dq fill=\(dqblue\(dq />
    </\f[B]pattern\f[R]>
    \f[I]<!\-\- Second pattern \-\->\f[R]
    <\f[B]pattern\f[R]
      id=\(dqpattern2\(dq
      x=\(dq100\(dq
      height=\(dq40\(dq
      width=\(dq40\(dq
      patternUnits=\(dquserSpaceOnUse\(dq>
      <\f[B]circle\f[R] cx=\(dq20\(dq cy=\(dq20\(dq r=\(dq10\(dq fill=\(dqred\(dq />
    </\f[B]pattern\f[R]>
  </\f[B]defs\f[R]>
  \f[I]<!\-\- Using the patterns \-\->\f[R]
  <\f[B]rect\f[R] x=\(dq0\(dq y=\(dq0\(dq width=\(dq100\(dq height=\(dq100\(dq fill=\(dqurl(#pattern1)\(dq />
  <\f[B]rect\f[R] x=\(dq100\(dq y=\(dq0\(dq width=\(dq100\(dq height=\(dq100\(dq fill=\(dqurl(#pattern2)\(dq />
</\f[B]svg\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
We can access the computed values of the \f[CR]x\f[R] attributes:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] patterns = document.querySelectorAll(\(dqpattern\(dq);

console.log(patterns[0].width.baseVal.value); \f[I]// output: 20\f[R]
console.log(patterns[1].width.baseVal.value); \f[I]// output: 40\f[R]
.EE
